Wall Street has caught M&A fever anticipating the incoming Trump
administration, but C.E.O.s may soon regret placing big bets on a scenario =
rife with what ifs=E2=80=A6

William D. Cohan ( https://puck.news/author/william-cohan/?utm_campaign=3DD=
ry+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F8%2F25%29&utm_content=3DDry+Powder+-+SUBSCRI=
BERS+%281%2F8%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&ut=
m_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )
William D. Cohan ( https://puck.news/author/william-cohan/?utm_campaign=3DD=
ry+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F8%2F25%29&utm_content=3DDry+Powder+-+SUBSCRI=
BERS+%281%2F8%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&ut=
m_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )

Wall Street is gearing up for a big year in M&A. The
dealmaker-in-chief is returning to the White House, regulations will suppos=
edly be easing, the U.S. stock markets remain near all-time highs, interest=
 rates seem to have stabilized along with inflation=E2=80=94and both, hopef=
ully, are headed down, at least at the Federal Reserve level. One thing I=
=E2=80=99ve learned over the years is that once the Wall Street deal machin=
e gets primed, there is no stopping it.

=C2=A0

But who wins and who loses in
all the dealmaking frenzy? Certainly among the winners are the bankers, who=
 manage to haul away billions in fees, and the deal principals, who always =
figure out ways to get paid. Who gets left holding the bag? Often the share=
holders of the companies being acquired or sold off. Did they sell out at t=
oo high a price, or too low? Should they hold on, or run for the exits?=C2=
=A0

A MESSAGE FROM OUR SPONSOR

salesforce ( https://www.salesforce.com/resources/research-reports/state-of=
-the-connected-customer/?d=3D701ed00000Eel0EAAR&nc=3D701ed000009E5QtAAK&utm=
_source=3DPuck&utm_medium=3Dtp_email&utm_campaign=3Damer_alllobaw&utm_conte=
nt=3DAMER-US-WebForm=E2=80=94PuckNewsletter-DryPowder-NativeTout1-Paid=E2=
=80=94FY25Q4_701ed00000Eel0EAAR&utm_term=3D&utm_campaign=3DDry+Powder+-+SUB=
SCRIBERS+%281%2F8%2F25%29&utm_content=3DDry+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F8%2=
F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c606=
17da42abd12a )

Some deals, of course, are easier to figure out than others. I
don=E2=80=99t think you=E2=80=99ll find a single investor who=E2=80=99d com=
plain about the $54.20 a share in cash they got from Elon Musk for Twitter.=
 And, in a bizarre twist of fate, Musk wouldn=E2=80=99t either. He probably=
 doesn=E2=80=99t care ( https://puck.news/the-x-djt-merger-deal-book/?utm_c=
ampaign=3DDry+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F8%2F25%29&utm_content=3DDry+Powde=
r+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F8%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcus=
tomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) that he=E2=80=99s lost the $24 bil=
lion in equity that he invested, or that he=E2=80=99s paying $1.3 billion, =
or so, in annual interest payments to keep current on the $13 billion of
Twitter bank debt. His net worth, now around $425 billion, has more than do=
ubled since the deal closed in October 2022, and he=E2=80=99s now taken on =
yet another role as our shadow president, with growing transatlantic ambiti=
ons ( https://puck.news/raheem-kassam-on-elon-musks-british-invasion/?utm_c=
ampaign=3DDry+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F8%2F25%29&utm_content=3DDry+Powde=
r+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F8%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcus=
tomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ). (Does Larry Ellison care that the=
 $1 billion he invested in Twitter is lost? Probably not. He=E2=80=99s now =
the world=E2=80=99s fourth-richest person,
with a net worth of around $200 billion.)

=C2=A0

Meanwhile, should the non-Redstone shareholders in Paramount Global sell ou=
t to the new owners on a pro-rata basis, or stay put and hope for a better =
day under the leadership of David Ellison, Jeff Shell, and RedBird Capital=
=E2=80=99s Gerry Cardinale? That=E2=80=99s a much tougher call. Paramount G=
lobal could
trade up into the $30-plus-per-share range, as its deal engineers are betti=
ng, once Skydance is combined with the Paramount studio, costs are taken ou=
t, and whatever the Ellisons have planned on the technology front is implem=
ented. But the stock could just as easily trade down as up. (As per usual, =
this is not investment advice.)

=C2=A0

There are a lot of what ifs. After all, even after using $1.5
billion of Ellison/RedBird cash to pay down Paramount Global=E2=80=99s debt=
, the combined company will still have around $14 billion of net debt. When=
 you cut right through it, the Ellison/RedBird deal for Paramount Global is=
 a sophisticated bet on the fate of a highly leveraged company. I=E2=80=99v=
e seen many leveraged recaps start off with excitement and promise only to =
fizzle out, with the shareholders who held on, hoping for the best, getting=
 screwed. One dated study, from 1995, found that 31 percent of all
leveraged recaps done between 1985 and 1988 came a cropper. (There haven=E2=
=80=99t been so many leveraged recaps since those days, given how poorly ma=
ny of them performed.)

=C2=A0

In any event, it=E2=80=99s clear that investors are still trying to figure =
out what to make of the new Paramount Global: Since the deal was struck som=
e six months ago, the stock has been treading water, down around 4 percent,=
 even as the S&P 500 has increased 7 percent
in the same period. That=E2=80=99s not a vote of confidence.

Spinning the
SpinCos
------------

It=E2=80=99s no coincidence that our friend David Zaslav
decided, just a few weeks after Comcast=E2=80=99s Brian Roberts announced t=
hat he was spinning off NBCU=E2=80=99s cable assets into a =E2=80=9Cwell-ca=
pitalized SpinCo=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94an announcement made after the election=
=E2=80=94to reorganize his Warner Bros. Discovery internally so that the co=
mpany is positioned to do the same thing with its own linear assets. Rich G=
reenfield at LightShed Partners wrote on Monday that he doesn=E2=80=99t see=
 why WBD needs to own the Food Network or HGTV, and that
they =E2=80=9Ccould find a better home inside NBCU=E2=80=99s SpinCo that wo=
uld like to own cable networks they can build digital ecosystems around,=E2=
=80=9D all amplifying Wall Street=E2=80=99s M&A arms race.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Rich added, =E2=80=9CCould CNN be more valuable inside Paramount or as part=
 of a CNN/CBS joint venture?=E2=80=9D The reason for these moves, I=E2=80=
=99m thinking, involves Donald Trump, but not because he=E2=80=99s promisin=
g to reduce the regulatory rigor on
Wall Street. Rather, because the chaos he sows is good for cable news=E2=80=
=94or at least it was during Trump I.

salesforce ( https://www.salesforce.com/resources/research-reports/state-of=
-the-connected-customer/?d=3D701ed00000Eel0EAAR&nc=3D701ed000009E5QtAAK&utm=
_source=3DPuck&utm_medium=3Dtp_email&utm_campaign=3Damer_alllobaw&utm_conte=
nt=3DAMER-US-WebForm=E2=80=94PuckNewsletter-DryPowder-NativeTout2-Paid=E2=
=80=94FY25Q4_701ed00000Eel0EAAR&utm_term=3D&utm_campaign=3DDry+Powder+-+SUB=
SCRIBERS+%281%2F8%2F25%29&utm_content=3DDry+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F8%2=
F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c606=
17da42abd12a )

Chances are that Roberts and Zaz still remember Les
Moonves=E2=80=99s quip that Trump=E2=80=99s brand of crazy =E2=80=9Cmay not=
 be good for America, but it=E2=80=99s damn good for CBS.=E2=80=9D Indeed, =
like so many other C.E.O.s, Zaz, Roberts, Bob Iger, and the younger Ellison=
 are betting their money bigtime on Trump. Not by parading down to Mar-a-La=
go like Mark Zuckerberg, or donating to Trump=E2=80=99s inauguration like T=
im Cook, or paying $40 million to license a documentary about Melania,
like Jeff Bezos=E2=80=94although Iger still needs to explain his decision t=
o cave to Trump, to the tune of $16 million, on the Stephanopoulos lawsuit=
=E2=80=94but in a more subtle way.

They=E2=80=99re hoping that the inevitable Trump follies will once again be=
 good for business, and will thereby bolster the ratings of their downtrodd=
en linear TV and cable networks. It=E2=80=99s a gamble, for sure. Obviously=
, if they=E2=80=99re right, and Trump is once again a boon for ratings, tho=
se spun-off
cable businesses will perform better than anticipated, making the spin offs=
 a success (at least for a while) and they will look very smart indeed and =
likely be rewarded by the markets. Unless, of course, investors wonder why =
they spun them off at all instead of keeping them, which would, of course, =
have the opposite effect.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

There was a time, before the pandemic and during peak Trump I, when
NBCU was generating close to $9 billion in adjusted EBITDA per year. That m=
ade all of NBCU worth around $100 billion. Not bad, considering Comcast bou=
ght NBCU from GE for around $30 billion after the 2008 financial crisis.=C2=
=A0

=C2=A0

However, according to Comcast=E2=80=99s public filings, NBCU generated only=
 around $3 billion in =E2=80=9Cadjusted EBITDA=E2=80=9D in 2023=E2=80=94dow=
n from $3.6 billion in 2022 and $5.1 billion in in 2021.
(Loyal readers know well my taste for these adjustments, but I=E2=80=99ll s=
ave my fury for another day=E2=80=A6) If the company generated substantiall=
y less than $3 billion of adjusted EBITDA in 2024, the narrative will be cl=
ear: The business is rapidly losing steam.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

We don=E2=80=99t yet know what the income statement will look like for the =
cable businesses Comcast plans to spin off, but as the parentco has
announced that it=E2=80=99s keeping NBC, Bravo, and Peacock, among other pi=
eces, there=E2=80=99s little question that SpinCo=E2=80=99s 2024 adjusted E=
BITDA will be well below the $3 billion that all of NBCU generated in 2023.=
 (For the first nine months of 2024, Comcast=E2=80=99s media division gener=
ated the same $2.8 billion that it did for the first nine months of 2023, b=
olstered I=E2=80=99m sure by the Olympics.)

=C2=A0

The big question, then, is
whether the crazy of Trump II will bring eyeballs back to MSNBC, CNN, and C=
NBC like it did during Trump I. If viewers return at the level they did bef=
ore, that would bode well for the proposed Comcast SpinCo and the likely WB=
D spinco, at least during the first two years of Trump II, when the propose=
d spin-offs are likely to occur. After that, who knows? But if ratings reco=
ver significantly, the Wall Street hype machine will pump up the SpinCos, b=
oth as publicly traded companies on their own and
as potential =E2=80=9Cplatform companies=E2=80=9D for rolling up other fadi=
ng cable assets. It might also give CBS and Paramount=E2=80=99s forlorn cab=
le channels the same kind of boost that Moonves once boasted about by sayin=
g the quiet part out loud.

=C2=A0

On the other hand, if Trump II doesn=E2=80=99t generate cable news viewersh=
ip equivalent to Trump I=E2=80=94or if Trump=E2=80=99s proposed health secr=
etary miraculously pushes through a ban on
pharmaceutical ads=E2=80=94it could spell curtains for these spincos. (Can =
you imagine MSNBC without pharma ads?) Trump is certainly trying to do his =
part via his ongoing bromance with Elon, his nutty cabinet picks, his call =
to deport millions, his plans to impose tariffs and to buy Greenland and re=
claim the Panama Canal.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

And yet, as faithful readers of my partner Dylan Byers know by now,
viewers have conspicuously tuned out this show. =E2=80=9CWhen a sports team=
 loses, its fans don=E2=80=99t hang around for the postgame show,=E2=80=9D =
Steve Battaglio recently wrote in the Los Angeles Times. =E2=80=9CThe same =
goes for the tribal habits of cable news audiences.=E2=80=9D Since the elec=
tion, he reported, MSNBC=E2=80=99s ratings have fallen 46 percent compared =
to the first 10 months of 2024. CNN=E2=80=99s ratings have fallen 33 percen=
t. Are people inured to Trump, and sick of his antics? Are they less concer=
ned
now that he=E2=80=99s term-limited to four years? Or have they simply moved=
 on from cable news as a format for getting their information? As one forme=
r leading Democratic politician said to me over the holidays, =E2=80=9CLet=
=E2=80=99s just all stay in our bubble until this whole thing passes.=E2=80=
=9D=C2=A0

=C2=A0

It certainly feels like there=E2=80=99s been a sea change, and the people w=
ho once watched MSNBC and CNN as a religious experience are now happy to tu=
ne out.
And while the Trump show might momentarily preserve some of the value of li=
beral (or center-left) news networks, that value is indeed fleeting, as Zaz=
 and Roberts ostensibly know well. This reality could spell trouble for the=
 M&A prospects of these spincos, and everything Hollywood and Wall Street h=
ave riding on these deals. Many of us were put off by what Moonves said sev=
en years ago about Trump and CBS. But he was right. Sequels, of course, rar=
ely generate as much cash.=C2=A0

