ter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;=
line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">It=E2=80=99s no coincidence that our friend <st=
rong>David Zaslav</strong>
decided, just a few weeks after Comcast=E2=80=99s <strong>Brian Roberts</st=
rong> announced that he was spinning off NBCU=E2=80=99s cable assets into a=
 =E2=80=9Cwell-capitalized SpinCo=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94an announcement made <em=
>after</em> the election=E2=80=94to reorganize his Warner Bros. Discovery i=
nternally so that the company is positioned to do the same thing with its <=
em>own</em> linear assets. <strong>Rich Greenfield</strong> at LightShed Pa=
rtners wrote on Monday that he doesn=E2=80=99t see why WBD needs to own the=
 Food Network or HGTV, and that
they =E2=80=9Ccould find a better home inside NBCU=E2=80=99s SpinCo that wo=
uld like to own cable networks they can build digital ecosystems around,=E2=
=80=9D all amplifying Wall Street=E2=80=99s M&amp;A arms race.=C2=A0</p><p =
style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">Rich=
 added, =E2=80=9CCould CNN be more valuable inside Paramount or as part of =
a CNN/CBS joint venture?=E2=80=9D The reason for these moves, I=E2=80=99m t=
hinking, involves <strong>Donald Trump</strong>, but not because he=E2=80=
=99s promising to reduce the regulatory rigor on
Wall Street. Rather, because the chaos he sows is good for cable news=E2=80=
=94or at least it was during Trump I.</p></div>
