<table class=3D"c4 np" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellsp=
acing=3D"0" role=3D"presentation" style=3D"mso-table-lspace:0pt;mso-table-r=
space:0pt;word-break:break-word;"><tbody><tr><td class=3D"r" style=3D"paddi=
ng-bottom:32px;"><div style=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39=
;Inter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0=
px;line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Chances are that Roberts and Zaz still rem=
ember <strong>Les
Moonves</strong>=E2=80=99s quip that Trump=E2=80=99s brand of crazy =E2=80=
=9Cmay not be good for America, but it=E2=80=99s damn good for CBS.=E2=80=
=9D Indeed, like so many other C.E.O.s, Zaz, Roberts, <strong>Bob Iger</str=
ong>, and the younger Ellison are betting their money <em>bigtime</em> on T=
rump. Not by parading down to Mar-a-Lago like <strong>Mark Zuckerberg</stro=
ng>, or donating to Trump=E2=80=99s inauguration like <strong>Tim Cook</str=
ong>, or paying $40 million to license a documentary about <strong>Melania<=
/strong>,
like <strong>Jeff Bezos</strong>=E2=80=94although Iger still needs to expla=
in his decision to cave to Trump, to the tune of $16 million, on the <stron=
g>Stephanopoulos</strong> lawsuit=E2=80=94but in a more subtle way. <br/><b=
r/>They=E2=80=99re hoping that the inevitable Trump follies will once again=
 be good for business, and will thereby bolster the ratings of their downtr=
odden linear TV and cable networks. It=E2=80=99s a gamble, for sure. Obviou=
sly, if they=E2=80=99re right, and Trump is once again a boon for ratings, =
those spun-off
cable businesses will perform better than anticipated, making the spin offs=
 a success (at least for a while) and they will look very smart indeed and =
likely be rewarded by the markets. Unless, of course, investors wonder <em>=
why</em> they spun them off at all instead of keeping them, which would, of=
 course, have the opposite effect.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bot=
tom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">There was a ti=
me, before the pandemic and during peak Trump I, when
NBCU was generating close to $9 billion in adjusted EBITDA per year. That m=
ade all of NBCU worth around $100 billion. Not bad, considering Comcast bou=
ght NBCU from GE for around $30 billion after the 2008 financial crisis.=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margi=
n:0;margin-bottom:0px;">However, according to Comcast=E2=80=99s public fili=
ngs, NBCU generated only around $3 billion in =E2=80=9Cadjusted EBITDA=E2=
=80=9D in 2023=E2=80=94down from $3.6 billion in 2022 and $5.1 billion in i=
n 2021.
(Loyal readers know well my taste for these <em>adjustments</em>, but I=E2=
=80=99ll save my fury for another day=E2=80=A6) If the company generated su=
bstantially less than $3 billion of adjusted EBITDA in 2024, the narrative =
will be clear: The business is rapidly losing steam.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0p=
x;">We don=E2=80=99t yet know what the income statement will look like for =
the cable businesses Comcast plans to spin off, but as the parentco has
announced that it=E2=80=99s keeping NBC, Bravo, and Peacock, among other pi=
eces, there=E2=80=99s little question that SpinCo=E2=80=99s 2024 adjusted E=
BITDA will be well below the $3 billion that all of NBCU generated in 2023.=
 (For the first nine months of 2024, Comcast=E2=80=99s media division gener=
ated the same $2.8 billion that it did for the first nine months of 2023, b=
olstered I=E2=80=99m sure by the Olympics.)</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-=
bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">The big que=
stion, then, is
whether the crazy of Trump II will bring eyeballs back to MSNBC, CNN, and C=
NBC like it did during Trump I. If viewers return at the level they did bef=
ore, that would bode well for the proposed Comcast SpinCo and the likely WB=
D spinco, at least during the first two years of Trump II, when the propose=
d spin-offs are likely to occur. After that, who knows? But if ratings reco=
ver significantly, the Wall Street hype machine will pump up the SpinCos, b=
oth as publicly traded companies on their own and
as potential =E2=80=9Cplatform companies=E2=80=9D for rolling up other fadi=
ng cable assets. It might also give CBS and Paramount=E2=80=99s forlorn cab=
le channels the same kind of boost that Moonves once boasted about by sayin=
g the quiet part out loud.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">On the other hand, if Trump=
 II doesn=E2=80=99t generate cable news viewership equivalent to Trump I=E2=
=80=94or if Trump=E2=80=99s proposed health secretary miraculously pushes t=
hrough a ban on
pharmaceutical ads=E2=80=94it could spell curtains for these spincos. (Can =
you imagine MSNBC without pharma ads?) Trump is certainly trying to do his =
part via his ongoing bromance with Elon, his nutty cabinet picks, his call =
to deport millions, his plans to impose tariffs and to buy Greenland and re=
claim the Panama Canal.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=
=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">And yet, as faithful rea=
ders of my partner <strong>Dylan Byers </strong>know by now,
viewers have conspicuously tuned out this show. =E2=80=9CWhen a sports team=
 loses, its fans don=E2=80=99t hang around for the postgame show,=E2=80=9D =
<strong>Steve Battaglio</strong> recently wrote in the <em>Los Angeles Time=
s</em>. =E2=80=9CThe same goes for the tribal habits of cable news audience=
s.=E2=80=9D Since the election, he reported, MSNBC=E2=80=99s ratings have f=
allen 46 percent compared to the first 10 months of 2024. CNN=E2=80=99s rat=
ings have fallen 33 percent. Are people inured to Trump, and sick of his an=
tics? Are they less concerned
now that he=E2=80=99s term-limited to four years? Or have they simply moved=
 on from cable news as a format for getting their information? As one forme=
r leading Democratic politician said to me over the holidays, =E2=80=9CLet=
=E2=80=99s just all stay in our bubble until this whole thing passes.=E2=80=
=9D=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D=
"margin:0;">It certainly feels like there=E2=80=99s been a sea change, and =
the people who once watched MSNBC and CNN as a religious experience are now=
 happy to tune out.
And while the Trump show might momentarily preserve some of the value of li=
beral (or center-left) news networks, that value is indeed fleeting, as Zaz=
 and Roberts ostensibly know well. This reality could spell trouble for the=
 M&amp;A prospects of these spincos, and everything Hollywood and Wall Stre=
et have riding on these deals. Many of us were put off by what Moonves said=
 seven years ago about Trump and CBS. But he was right. Sequels, of course,=
 rarely generate as much cash.=C2=A0</p></div>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
